    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "A social media app is learning how to compare usernames so they can sort them alphabetically. The app will use the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareTo()</code> method to compare two usernames.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">SocialMedia</code> class, complete the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareUsernames()</code> method. This method should:\r\n\r\n- Use the instance variables <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">user1</code> and <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">user2</code>\r\n- Return the result of <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">user1.compareTo(user2)</code>\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">SocialMediaRunner</code> class, create a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">SocialMedia</code> object with two usernames and call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareUsernames()</code> method. Print the result.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareTo()</code> returns:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>a negative number if the first string comes before the second</li>\r\n  <li>zero if the two strings are equal</li>\r\n  <li>a positive number if the first string comes after the second</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n",
